examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. As part of routine antenatal screening, her urine nucleic acid amplification test returns positive for \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythromycin for four days","Single dose azithromycin","Defer treatment until after delivery","Doxycycline for seven days","Amoxicillin for four days"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has been diagnosed with \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E infection during routine antenatal screening. Untreated chlamydia in pregnancy is associated with adverse outcomes including premature rupture of membranes, preterm labour, and postpartum endometritis. The newborn may develop conjunctivitis or pneumonia if exposed during delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E (1g orally) is the recommended first-line treatment for chlamydia in pregnancy. It is safe, well-tolerated, and has excellent compliance due to the single-dose regimen. Treatment efficacy is around 97%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythromycin for four days\u003C/strong\u003E is an inadequate duration of treatment. While erythromycin is safe in pregnancy, the standard course is seven days, and it is less preferred due to gastrointestinal side effects and the need for multiple doses which may affect compliance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeferring treatment\u003C/strong\u003E until after delivery is inappropriate as it risks complications for both mother and baby. Prompt treatment is essential to prevent adverse pregnancy outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in pregnancy as it can cause dental staining and affect bone development in the fetus. It should not be used at any stage of pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E for four days is an inadequate duration of treatment. While amoxicillin is safe in pregnancy, it has lower cure rates compared to azithromycin and requires a longer course of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollow-up testing should be performed three weeks after treatment to ensure cure. Sexual partners from the last six months should be notified, tested, and treated to prevent reinfection. Condom use should be advised until both partners have completed treatment and follow-up testing confirms cure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High risk pregnant women should be screened for Chlamydia trachomatis infection at their first antenatal visit.","Azithromycin is the first-line treatment for chlamydia in pregnancy.","Partners of women with chlamydia must be treated to prevent reinfection."],"references":["Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases (ASID). Management of perinatal infections. East Melbourne: ASID; 2022 [cited 2024 Nov 5]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44586"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14884"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44586"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-05T14:57:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T14:58:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7575"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59175"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relat